    "    YY, XX = np.meshgrid(yy, xx)\n",
    "    xy = np.vstack([XX.ravel(), YY.ravel()]).T\n",
    "\n",
    "    # decision_function gives signed distance from hyperplane\n",
    "    Z = model.decision_function(xy).reshape(XX.shape)\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
    "    plt.contour(XX, YY, Z, colors='k', levels=[-1, 0, 1],\n",
    "                alpha=0.5, linestyles=['--', '-', '--'])\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, cmap=plt.cm.Paired,\n",
    "                edgecolors='k', s=40, label='data points')\n",
    "\n",
    "    if plot_support:\n",
    "        plt.scatter(\n",
    "            model.support_vectors_[:, 0],\n",
    "            model.support_vectors_[:, 1],\n",
    "            label='support vectors',\n",
    "            s=120,\n",
    "            linewidth=1.5,\n",
    "            edgecolor='blue',\n",
    "            facecolors='none'\n",
    "        )\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.title('SVM decision boundary and support vectors')\n",
    "    plt.legend()\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "plot_svm_2D(X2, y2, svm2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "svm_sv_answer",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Question:** Which objects are identified as "support" vectors?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Answer:** Support vectors are the training examples that lie **on or inside** the margin (the two dashed lines at distance 1 from the decision boundary). They are the closest points to the hyperplane from each class. The SVM hyperplane is determined entirely by these points; removing any other training example would not change the model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "lr_2d_intro",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Unlike SVM, logistic regression approximates $p(y=+1|x)$ at every point. Let's visualise this probability distribution."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "lr_2d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "lr2 = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)\n",
    "lr2.fit(X2, y2)\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_logreg_2D(X, y, model):\n",
    "    xx = np.linspace(X[:, 0].min() - 0.5, X[:, 0].max() + 0.5, 100)\n",
    "    yy = np.linspace(X[:, 1].min() - 0.5, X[:, 1].max() + 0.5, 100)\n",
    "    YY, XX = np.meshgrid(yy, xx)\n",
    "    xy = np.vstack([XX.ravel(), YY.ravel()]).T\n",
    "\n",
    "    # probability of positive class at each grid point\n",
    "    Z = model.predict_proba(xy)[:, 1]\n",
    "    Z = Z.reshape((xx.shape[0], -1)).T\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
    "    image = plt.imshow(\n",
    "        Z,\n",
    "        interpolation='nearest',\n",
    "        extent=(xx.min(), xx.max(), yy.min(), yy.max()),\n",
    "        aspect='auto',\n",
    "        origin='lower',\n",
    "        cmap=plt.cm.PuOr_r\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, cmap=plt.cm.Paired,\n",
    "                edgecolors='k', s=40)\n",
    "    plt.colorbar(image, label='P(y=1|x)')\n",
    "    plt.title('Logistic Regression probability distribution')\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "plot_logreg_2D(X2, y2, lr2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "lr_uncertain_answer",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Question:** How is the region where $p(y=+1|x) = 0.5$ visualised?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Answer:** The 0.5 probability contour appears as a **straight line** — the transition from purple to orange in the centre of the image. Theoretically this is because logistic regression models $p(y=1|x) = \\sigma(w^\\top x + b)$, and $\\sigma(z) = 0.5$ exactly when $z = 0$, i.e. $w^\\top x + b = 0$, which is a linear (hyperplane) equation. So the decision boundary is always a hyperplane, identical to the SVM boundary (though trained differently)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "task2_intro",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### **Task 2. Probability Calibration** (1 point)\n",
    "\n",
    "First, fix the buggy `plot_calibration_curve` function. Two bugs:\n",
    "1. `(l - r) / 2` should be `(l + r) / 2` (midpoint, not negative half-width)\n",
    "2. `np.min(... == 1)` should be `np.mean(... == 1)` (fraction of positives, not minimum)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "calib_curve",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_calibration_curve(y_test, preds, label='model'):\n",
    "    bin_middle_points = []\n",
    "    bin_real_ratios = []\n",
    "    n_bins = 10\n",
    "    for i in range(n_bins):\n",
    "        l = 1.0 / n_bins * i\n",
    "        r = 1.0 / n_bins * (i + 1)\n",
    "        # BUG 1 FIX: midpoint is (l + r)/2, not (l - r)/2\n",
    "        bin_middle_points.append((l + r) / 2)\n",
    "        mask = (preds >= l) & (preds < r)\n",
    "        if mask.sum() == 0:\n",
    "            bin_real_ratios.append(np.nan)\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            # BUG 2 FIX: mean (fraction of positives), not min\n",
    "            bin_real_ratios.append(np.mean(y_test[mask] == 1))\n",
    "    plt.plot(bin_middle_points, bin_real_ratios, marker='o', label=label)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generate data same as Task 1.1\n",
    "X_cal, y_cal = make_classification(\n",
    "    n_samples=10000, n_features=10, n_informative=5, n_redundant=5, random_state=42\n",
    ")\n",
    "X_cal_train, X_cal_test, y_cal_train, y_cal_test = train_test_split(\n",
    "    X_cal, y_cal, test_size=0.3, random_state=42\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Train models\n",
    "svm_cal = LinearSVC(C=1.0, max_iter=5000, random_state=42)\n",
    "svm_cal.fit(X_cal_train, y_cal_train)\n",
    "svm_dec = svm_cal.decision_function(X_cal_test)\n",
    "svm_proba = (svm_dec - svm_dec.min()) / (svm_dec.max() - svm_dec.min())  # scale to [0,1]\n",
    "\n",
    "lr_cal = LogisticRegression(C=1.0, max_iter=1000, random_state=42)\n",
    "lr_cal.fit(X_cal_train, y_cal_train)\n",
    "lr_proba = lr_cal.predict_proba(X_cal_test)[:, 1]\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(7, 6))\n",
    "plot_calibration_curve(y_cal_test, svm_proba, label='SVM')\n",
    "plot_calibration_curve(y_cal_test, lr_proba, label='Logistic Regression')\n",
    "plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', label='Perfect calibration')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Mean predicted probability')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Fraction of positives')\n",
    "plt.title('Calibration curves')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.ylim(-0.05, 1.05)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "calib_answer",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Question:** Are the curves for SVM and LR well calibrated?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Answer:** Logistic regression is **well calibrated** — its curve lies close to the diagonal, because the sigmoid output is trained to approximate the posterior class probability directly. The SVM is **poorly calibrated**: its decision-function scores are distances from the margin, not probabilities. After linear rescaling to [0, 1] the curve is typically S-shaped (sigmoidal distortion) — it is too flat in the middle (model is over-confident near the boundary) and too steep at the extremes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "logloss_brier",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.metrics import log_loss, brier_score_loss\n",
    "\n",
    "print('--- LogLoss and Brier Score ---')\n",
    "for name, preds in [('SVM (scaled)', svm_proba), ('Logistic Regression', lr_proba)]:\n",
    "    ll = log_loss(y_cal_test, preds)\n",
    "    bs = brier_score_loss(y_cal_test, preds)\n",
    "    print(f'{name:25s}  LogLoss: {ll:.4f}  Brier: {bs:.4f}')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Histograms of predictions\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))\n",
    "axes[0].hist(svm_proba, bins=30, edgecolor='k')\n",
    "axes[0].set_title('SVM score distribution')\n",
    "axes[1].hist(lr_proba, bins=30, edgecolor='k')\n",
    "axes[1].set_title('LR probability distribution')\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "hist_answer",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Question:** How do the distributions differ?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Answer:** The SVM scores, after linear rescaling, are spread across [0, 1] roughly uniformly, with many values concentrated near 0 and 1 because the margin pushes samples away from the boundary. Logistic regression probabilities are more concentrated near 0 and 1 as well, but in a meaningful way reflecting actual posterior probability — the model is appropriately more confident for points far from the boundary. SVM's LogLoss and Brier Score are worse because its scaled scores do not represent calibrated probabilities."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "calib_svm",
