  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "task13",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### **Task 13. The Key Metric** (1 point)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Question:** What is more important — precision or recall?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Answer:** In this scenario, **recall** is arguably more important. Each missed positive client (false negative) costs us the full $10 revenue, whereas each false positive costs us only $2 (call cost). Since revenue >> call cost, we prefer to cast a wide net (high recall) to avoid missing paying clients. However, if recall becomes too high (we call everyone), costs may exceed revenues. The optimal threshold balances these: it's the point where marginal revenue from one more call equals marginal cost."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "threshold_tune",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold\n",
    "\n",
    "thresholds = np.arange(0.01, 1.0, 0.01)\n",
    "profits_by_thresh = []\n",
    "\n",
    "skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Collect all out-of-fold probabilities once\n",
    "oof_proba = np.zeros(len(y_bank))\n",
    "oof_y = np.zeros(len(y_bank))\n",
    "\n",
    "for train_idx, test_idx in skf.split(X_bank, y_bank):\n",
    "    X_tr, X_te = X_bank.iloc[train_idx], X_bank.iloc[test_idx]\n",
    "    y_tr, y_te = y_bank.iloc[train_idx], y_bank.iloc[test_idx]\n",
    "\n",
    "    prep = ColumnTransformer([\n",
    "        ('ohe', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse_output=False), cat_bank),\n",
    "        ('sc',  StandardScaler(), num_bank)\n",
    "    ])\n",
    "    X_tr_enc = prep.fit_transform(X_tr)\n",
    "    X_te_enc = prep.transform(X_te)\n",
    "\n",
    "    model = LogisticRegression(C=best_C_bank, max_iter=1000, random_state=42)\n",
    "    model.fit(X_tr_enc, y_tr)\n",
    "\n",
    "    oof_proba[test_idx] = model.predict_proba(X_te_enc)[:, 1]\n",
    "    oof_y[test_idx] = y_te.values\n",
    "\n",
    "# Sweep thresholds over OOF predictions\n",
    "for thresh in thresholds:\n",
    "    pred = (oof_proba >= thresh).astype(int)\n",
    "    profits_by_thresh.append(compute_profit(oof_y, pred))\n",
    "\n",
    "best_thresh = thresholds[np.argmax(profits_by_thresh)]\n",
    "print(f'Best threshold: {best_thresh:.2f}  Profit: {max(profits_by_thresh):.1f}')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(9, 4))\n",
    "plt.plot(thresholds, profits_by_thresh)\n",
    "plt.axvline(best_thresh, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Best threshold = {best_thresh:.2f}')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Binarization threshold')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Total profit (OOF)')\n",
    "plt.title('Profit vs. Threshold')\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "thresh_answer",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Question:** Do you notice any pattern?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Answer:** The optimal threshold is typically **below 0.5** (often around 0.2–0.4), reflecting that recall matters more here. Since calling a client costs only $2 while a successful call brings $10, it pays to call even clients for whom the model has moderate confidence. The profit curve rises steeply as the threshold drops from 1 (no calls) toward the optimum, then falls gradually as we make more low-value calls. This pattern is consistent across runs because it is driven by the fixed cost/revenue ratio."
   ]
  },
