   "source": [
    "**Explanation:**\n",
    "\n",
    "OvR trains K classifiers (one per class), each distinguishing that class from all others. OvO trains K(K-1)/2 classifiers, one per pair. With K=3 classes: OvR=3, OvO=3 (equal here; differences grow with more classes). OvO classifiers train on smaller, balanced subsets (only two classes each), which can be faster per classifier but more classifiers overall. OvR tends to suffer from class imbalance in each sub-problem; OvO avoids this. Quality is often similar for logistic regression since it already has multinomial support, but OvO can outperform OvR when classes overlap."
   ]
